Level Up Your Argo CD Game with ApplicationSet

Abhinav Sonkar
Follow
Oct 3 · 4 min read

One of my favourite tools in the Kubernetes ecosystem is Argo CD. It takes the theoretical concepts of GitOps and turns it into a pragmatic, user-friendly tool with a UI to boot. Knowing that it is watching your Git repository (desired state), comparing it continuously with the manifests in Kubernetes (live state) and alerting you for any skew is exactly the kind of automation a DevOps engineer needs.

If you are unfamiliar with Argo CD, I highly recommend to explore it and add it to your arsenal. The rest of the blog assumes you have basic familiarity.

The Too Many Apps Problem

I use Argo CD to deploy a bunch of business applications as I have explained in The Kubernetes Ownership Model. As the number of applications starts to grow, a unique problem surfaces. It becomes a mess to manage all the Argo CD Application resources. I deploy Argo CD via the Helm Charts, so I am able to use the values.yaml to declare the Argo CD Application resources. But imagine having hundreds of Application specifications in a single values.yaml. Not fun.

Initially, the Argo CD user community came up with an interesting solution. Since the Argo CD Application CustomResourceDefinition (CRD) is simply a combination of a source (Git repository) and a destination (Kubernetes cluster), it can be used to deploy another Argo CD Application itself! This is known as the App of Apps Pattern. Now instead of declaring all those Applications inside values.yaml, I need to declare only one Application (the App of Apps) and move the specifications of all other Applications in a Git repository.

While this is cool, notice that it doesn’t really solve the problem. It just moves the problem somewhere else. If you are smart, you can move those bunch of Applications in a Git repository managed by another team and make it somebody else’s problem ;-)

Argo CD ApplicationSet

The Argo CD team noticed the innovative use of App of Apps pattern and turned it into a more generic, powerful solution called ApplicationSet. It is another CRD which generates Argo CD Application.

While the Application CRD consists of source and destination, the ApplicationSet CRD consists of Generators and Application template. The Generators generate key-value parameters that are substituted in the Application template to render the actual Application resources.

When to Use Argo CD ApplicationSet

Firstly, you don’t need to use ApplicationSet if you don’t have the “Too Many Apps” problem. Secondly, if you do have too many applications, consider if some of those applications are functionally similar. Ask the question, what does the ArgoCD applications represent?

  1. Maybe the applications represent “tenants” in your system. If each tenant requires a bunch of pods to be deployed, you need an ArgoCD Application.
  2. Maybe the applications represent “teams” in your company. As a Platform team, you want to deploy a bunch of pods for each DevOps team.
  3. Maybe the applications represent a “combination of tools” that are deployed in every Kubernetes cluster.
  4. Maybe the applications represent “environments” of software lifecycle.

In all the above scenarios, you have a bunch of Applications that are similar and need to be…

  1. Deployed from different Git repositories/branches.
  2. or deployed to multiple/different Kubernetes clusters.
  3. or deployed to different namespaces of the same Kubernetes cluster.

All of these use cases can be easily implemented with ApplicationSet.

What “Generators” to use?

There are many Generators available but my preferred one is the Git Files Generator. This delegates the key-value parameters generation logic to a JSON/YAML file in, you guessed it, a Git repository (crazy, I know).

Here’s an example JSON file (it can contain any parameters, no limitations):

{
  "tenant": {
    "owner": "contact@tenant.com",
    "name": "tenant",
    "id": "tenantId",
    "region": "eastus2"
  },
  "k8s_cluster": {
    "owner": "admin@company.com",
    "name": "customer-prod",
    "address": "https://1.2.3.4"
  }
}

The parameters defined above can be used in the ApplicationSet as below:

apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: ApplicationSet
metadata:
  name: tenant-apps
spec:
  generators:
    - git:
        repoURL: git@github.com:example-tenant-apps.git
        revision: HEAD
        files:
          - path: "argocd/tenant-discovery/**/config.json"
  template:
    metadata:
      name: '{{tenant.name}}'
    spec:
      project: default
      source:
        repoURL: git@github.com:example-tenant-configurations.git
        targetRevision: HEAD
        path: '{{tenant.region}}/tenants/{{tenant.name}}'
        helm:
          valueFiles:
            - values.{{tenant.name}}.yaml
      destination:
        server: '{{k8s_cluster.address}}'
        namespace: prod
      syncPolicy: { }

Notice the Application template section. Some of the fields like values.{{tenant.name}}.yaml are populated via the parameters that will be replaced by the Generator. Other fields like namespace: prod are hard-coded and will remain same for all Applications. It is really up to you how static or dynamic you want your ApplicationSet to be.

Another interesting feature is the possibility of discovering multiple JSON/YAML files by using ** in path field. Adding a new tenant requires only adding another folder under argocd/tenant-discovery with its own config.json. The Generator will automatically discover the new tenant and create another Argo CD Application resource.

Deploying ApplicationSet Declaratively

While Argo CD Applications can be deployed declaratively using Argo CD Helm Charts, it does not yet support ApplicationSet deployment. No worries, Argo CD to the rescue! Remember that Argo CD Application can be used to deploy anything… including ApplicationSet itself!

This can be seen in the header image above. The Application prod-appsets deploys multiple ApplicationSet resources which in turn deploy multiple Applications. Argo CD is able to handle this and manage the lifecycle of all applications correctly.

Conclusion

Argo CD is a powerful Continuous Deployment tool based on GitOps. Combined with ApplicationSet it gives you the power to deploy a number of Applications without having to explicitly declare them anywhere. Make use of it to deploy applications for multiple environments, teams, customers or anything else you can think of! If you are using ApplicationSet, I would love to know more about it.
